subSubSection.paragraph:
Quedius capitalis
Eppelsheim 1892
, 329 (original description); 
Gridelli 1924
, 40 (characters); 
Coiffait 1978
, 148 (characters and illustration of aedeagus); 
Kadyrov et al. 2014a
, 31 and 2014b, 49 (distributional records).

Male: protarsi with tarsomeres 1-4 dilated stronger than in females. Sternite VIII with weak triangular medio-apical emargination; tergite X triangular with setae; sternite IX elongate, gradually narrowed apically, with moderately wide and long basal portion and obtusely rounded apical margin with numerous setae. Aedeagus (Fig. 7C, D): median lobe parallel-sided with broad and obtuse apex and tooth located near apex (Fig. 7 C). Paramere rhomboid sharply narrowing apicad; its apex almost reaching apex of median lobe, with two pairs of apical setae and two pairs of lateral setae below apex; 
paramere
(underside) with ca. 4-8 sensory peg setae in each of two sinuate lateral rows that extend basad over pairs of lateral setae (Fig. 7D).
